node.title: Belarus president lashed for 'inhuman' migrant crisis
node.description: The European Commission has accused Belarus's authoritarian leader of luring migrants with the false promise of easy entry to the EU as part of an "inhuman, gangster-style approach".

node.title: World headed for 2.4C warming despite climate summit - report
node.description: Despite pledges made at the climate summit COP26, the world is still nowhere near its goals on limiting global temperature rise, a new analysis shows.

node.title: Coal burning pushes rise in NZ emissions
node.description: New Zealand's industry and household greenhouse gas emissions rose 4.8 percent in the three months to June, mainly off the back of coal burning to generate electricity.

node.title: U.S. Holocaust Museum Says China ‘May Be Committing Genocide’ Against Uyghurs
node.description: Its report found that the government’s attacks against the group of Muslims in Xinjiang had escalated and most likely included “forced sterilization, sexual violence, enslavement, torture, and forcible transfer.”

node.title: NFL Levies Fines to Aaron Rodgers, Green Bay Packers for Breaking COVID Protocols
node.description: The team was fined $300,000 while Rodgers and another player were each fined $14,650.

node.title: 41yo truck driver charged over ambulance crash killing nurse and elderly patient
node.description: A man has been charged over the deaths of nurse Ray Wyeth and his 87-year-old patient, who were killed when his truck hit the ambulance they were travelling in west of Rockhampton last month.

node.title: Teenage driver and passenger accused of breaching WA hard border by speeding through checkpoint
node.description: A 17-year-old boy driving from New South Wales and his 24-year-old passenger are charged after their car allegedly sped through the West Australian border checkpoint at Eucla, failing to stop for police.

node.title: Dutch government rejects hundreds of millions of pieces of protective gear.
node.description: By Claire Moses

node.title: Macron announces a new vaccine rule for people 65 or older in France.
node.description: Though the country has a high vaccination rate, new coronavirus cases and hospital admissions have been increasing in recent weeks.

node.title: Facial recognition tech put on hold in Adelaide amidst privacy concerns
node.description: Some $3 million will be spent on a new Adelaide surveillance network, but a council proposal passed overnight means police cannot access its facial recognition capabilities without laws to protect privacy.

node.title: Up-and-coming Hawthorn player tests positive to COVID-19
node.description: Finn Maginness is in quarantine, as Hawthorn confirms all its players have had at least one dose of the COVID-19 vaccine.

node.title: Marie Antoinette's diamond bracelets sell for millions at auction
node.description: The opulent bracelets, among the rare pieces of jewellery from the ill-fated French royal that are still up for public sale today, went under the hammer at a Christie's auction in Geneva.

node.title: All Auckland, Waikato schools to reopen next week
node.description: Auckland and Waikato students in years 1 to 10 will return to face-to-face learning from 17 November, while timelines will be eased for national curriculum and assessments for other students. Video

node.title: Judge denies Trump's request to block release of documents to January 6 committee
node.description: Former President Trump sued the committee and the archives in an attempt to halt the transfer of his records.

node.title: Judge Rejects Trump’s Bid to Keep Papers Secret in Jan. 6 Inquiry
node.description: But a Trump lawyer has signaled an intent to appeal the ruling, which raises novel issues about an ex-president’s executive privilege powers.

node.title: COP26: Obama chides China and Russia, urges support for poorer nations
node.description: Former US President Barack Obama has called for rich nations to end years of deadlock with developing countries over cash for climate change, and criticised China and Russia.

node.title: Obama addresses High Ambition Coalition countries at COP26
node.description: Explainer - New Zealand is part of a coalition pushing for more progressive climate policies in Glasgow.

node.title: Green Bay Packers, Aaron Rodgers and Allen Lazard fined for COVID violations
node.description: Aaron Rodgers tested positive for COVID-19 last week, and later revealed he was not vaccinated.

node.title: Emotion and Grit Power Kenyans in New York City Marathon
node.description: Albert Korir won the men’s division in 2:08:22, while Peres Jepchirchir won the women’s division in 2:22:39 after also winning at the Tokyo Games.

node.title: Tuvalu minister gives COP26 speech standing knee-deep in the sea
node.description: Simon Kofe wears a suit and tie at a lectern set up in the sea, speaking from what used to be dry land to draw attention to Tuvalu's struggle against rising sea levels.

node.title: Tyson Fury '50 per cent fit' for fight with Deontay Wilder
node.description: Tyson Fury was dealing with a serious injury during his heavyweight championship fight with Deontay Wilder and has since required surgery, his father John says.

node.title: Paramedic's bid to be exempt from 'morally repugnant' vax mandate struck down in court
node.description: Veteran health worker and Snowy Valleys Deputy Mayor John Larter's legal push to have part of the state's public health orders declared invalid is rejected in the Supreme Court.

node.title: Farmers need support to adjust to increase in dry conditions, reports say
node.description: Regional councils and primary sector bodies are being told they need to act now to better support farmers to grow food under increasingly dry conditions.

node.title: BNZ annual net profit rises by 74% to $1.3bn
node.description: Another major retail bank has seen its profits surge, driven by the strong economic rebound from Covid-19, high demand for mortgages and a lack of bad debts.

node.title: Fonterra continues plans to vote on future of capital structure
node.description: Dairy giant Fonterra is pressing on with plans to hold a vote on the future of its capital structure, despite not yet having government support for the proposal.

node.title: Air NZ preparing for summer holiday flights ahead of govt border restriction announcement
node.description: Air New Zealand's chief executive estimates it could take up to six weeks to prepare to fly New Zealanders to their chosen Christmas destinations, so it needs a decision on borders urgently. Audio
